    <exercise xml:id="ex-describing-a-enlargement">
        <stack label="stk-describing-a-enlargement" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-1-Similarity-and-Enlargement/2-1-2-Enlargement/Describing-a-enlargement.xml"/>
    </exercise>
   
    <exercises xml:id="exercises-enlargement">

      <exercise xml:id="auto_x7thfmib">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_84lfpsww">
                A triangle with the verticies <m>X\, (4,0)</m>, <m>Y\, (6,3)</m> and <m>Z\, (5,4)</m> is enlarged.If the centre of enlargment is <m>(1,1)</m>, find the co-ordinates of the image of the triangle when the scale factor is:
            </p>

            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               <m>-2</m> 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
         </statement>
         <answer>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           <md>
                                <mrow>X': (1 + (-2)(4-1), 1 + (-2)(0-1)) = (1-6, 1+2) = (-5,3)</mrow>
                                <mrow>Y': (1 + (-2)(6-1), 1 + (-2)(3-1)) = (1-10, 1-4) = (-9,-3)</mrow>
                                <mrow>Z': (1 + (-2)(5-1), 1 + (-2)(4-1)) = (1-8, 1-6) = (-7,-5)</mrow>
                            </md> 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>X': (1 + 0.5(4-1), 1 + 0.5(0-1)) = (1+1.5, 1-0.5) = (2.5,0.5)</mrow>
                                <mrow>Y': (1 + 0.5(6-1), 1 + 0.5(3-1)) = (1+2.5, 1+1) = (3.5,2)</mrow>
                                <mrow>Z': (1 + 0.5(5-1), 1 + 0.5(4-1)) = (1+2, 1+1.5) = (3,2.5)</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
         </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_u0b5qcmv">
         <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_1w1ioflt">
                    Points <m>A\, (2,6)</m>, <m>B\, (4,6)</m>, and  <m>C\, (4,2)</m> are the vertices of a triangle. Taking point <m>(0,2)</m> as the centre of enlargement, find the coordinates of its image when the scale factor is <m>-1</m>.
                </p>
         </statement>
         <answer>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>A': (0 + (-1)(2-0), 2 + (-1)(6-2)) = (-2, -2)</mrow>
                    <mrow>B': (0 + (-1)(4-0), 2 + (-1)(6-2)) = (-4, -2)</mrow>
                    <mrow>C': (0 + (-1)(4-0), 2 + (-1)(2-2)) = (-4, 2)</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
         </answer>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="auto_uyxjftoc">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_xp1w994w">
                Points <m>P\,(1,4)</m>, <m>Q\, (3,4)</m> and <m>R\, (3,1)</m> are verticies of a triangle. Taking the origin as the centre of enlargement, find the image when the scale factor is;
            </p>

            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               <m>-\frac{1}{4}</m> 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>-3</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>P': (0 + (-1/4)\times(1-0), 0 + (-1/4)\times(4-0)) = (-0.25, -1)</mrow>
                                <mrow>Q': (0 + (-1/4)\times(3-0), 0 + (-1/4)\times(4-0)) = (-0.75, -1)</mrow>
                                <mrow>R': (0 + (-1/4)\times(3-0), 0 + (-1/4)\times(1-0)) = (-0.75, -0.25)</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>P': (-3, -12)</mrow>
                                <mrow>Q': (-9, -12)</mrow>
                                <mrow>R': (-9, -3)</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>P': (2, 8)</mrow>
                                <mrow>Q': (6, 8)</mrow>
                                <mrow>R': (6, 2)</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </answer>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="auto_o2tce22m">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_ly22ijik">
                A square measures <m>5</m> cm by <m>9</m> cm. Find the corresponding measurements of the image of the square after an enlargement with scale factor of <m>-2.</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>Width': 5 \times 2 = 10\ \text{cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow>Height': 9 \times 2 = 18\ \text{cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </answer>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="auto_zsrk0c6b">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_hw5l60wk">
                A photograph is enlarged so that its width increases from <m>10</m> cm to <m>25</m> cm. If the original height is <m>15</m> cm, find the new height.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>k = \frac{25}{10} = 2.5</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{New height} = 15 \times 2.5 = 37.5\ \text{cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </answer>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="auto_5s2k2x8x">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_ybgga0r3">
                A map has a scale of <m>1:50,000</m>. If the distance between two cities on the map is <m>8</m> cm, find the actual distance.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <m>Actual distance = 8 \times 50,000 = 400,000\; \text{cm} = 4\; \text{km}</m>
            </p>
        </answer>
      </exercise>
        
     </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide pre-drawn coordinate grids. Use a step-by-step checklist: (1) Plot original, (2) Draw rays from centre, (3) Multiply distances, (4) Plot image. Limit to whole-number scale factors only.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>Complete all practice problems as described. Encourage peer explanation of method. Use digital interactive checkpoints.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Non-origin centre enlargement. Get students to draw an enlargement of an object with centre of enlargement away from the origin.</line><line>Given <m>P(1,2)</m>, <m>Q(3,2)</m>, <m>R(2,4)</m> with centre <m>C(1,1)</m> and scale factor <m>k=3</m>, get them to find the image.</line><line> If needed, suggest translation to the origin, and use <m>\text{Image} = \text{Centre} + k \times (\text{Point} - \text{Centre})</m>. E.g. <m>P' = (1,1) + 3 \times ((1,2)-(1,1)) = (1,1) + 3(0,1) = (1,4)</m>. Area scales by <m>k^2</m>.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Extension Activities</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Triangle <m>A(2,1)</m>, <m>B(4,1)</m>, <m>C(3,3)</m>. Centre of enlargement <m>(1,0)</m>, scale factor <m>2</m>.
                        <m>A' = (1,0) + 2((2,1)-(1,0)) = (1,0)+2(1,1) = (3,2)</m>.
                        <m>B' = (1,0) + 2((4,1)-(1,0)) = (1,0)+2(3,1) = (7,2)</m>.
                        <m>C' = (1,0) + 2((3,3)-(1,0)) = (1,0)+2(2,3) = (5,6)</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Area Investigation:</alert> Area of <m>\triangle ABC = 3</m> sq units. Area of <m>\triangle A'B'C'</m> (scale factor <m>2</m>) <m>= 12</m> sq units. Ratio <m>= \frac{12}{3} = 4 = 2^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

